Parametric Assumptions

What are some distributions?

  • Binomial: represents observations that fall into one of two categories (e.g., present/absent, yes/no, male/female, etc.)
    • One category is designated success (p) (this is an arbitrary designation) and the probability of a failure is considered 1- p
    • Number of successes of n trials (successes + failures = trials) - Trials are essentially the number of observations
    • One parameter: the probability of success on any single trial (\( \phi \))

\( [z | n, \phi \)] = \( binomial(z | n, \phi \)) = \( \binom{n}{z} \phi^z (1 - \phi)^{n-z} \)

  • z and n are integers
  • \( \phi \) is a real number between 0 and 1
A <- rbinom(1000, 100, 0.4)
hist(A, freq = FALSE)

Parameters define the shape of a distribution

  • Poisson: number of successes that will occur within a particular unit of time or space and the occurrence of each success is independent of the other occurrences
    • One parameter: intensity (\( \lambda \)) - the average number of observations per unit

\( [z \mid \lambda \)] = \( Poisson(z \mid \lambda \)) = \( \displaystyle \frac {\lambda^z}{z!}e^-\lambda \)

B <- rpois(1000, 1)
hist(B, freq = FALSE)

  • Normal: Gaussian/Bell; continuous probability distribution for values from -infinity to infinity
    • Two parameters: mean and standard deviation
    • The normal distribution is component of parametric distribution

\( [z \mid \mu, \sigma^2 \)] = \( normal(z \mid \mu, \sigma^2 \)) = \( \displaystyle \frac {1}{\sigma \sqrt{2 \pi}} e^{-\displaystyle \frac{(z- \mu)^2}{2 \sigma^2}} \)

C <- rnorm(1000, 0, 1)
hist(C, freq = FALSE)

  • Lognormal: continuous probability distribution; where the logarithm makes the distribution normal
    • If a variable represents the product of other variables, it can be expected that it will follow a lognormal distribution

\( [z \mid \alpha, \beta \)] = \( lognormal(z \mid \alpha, \beta \)) = \( \displaystyle \frac {1}{z \sqrt{2 \pi \beta^2}} e^{-\displaystyle \frac{(log(z)-\alpha)^2}{2 \beta^2}} \) 

D <- rlnorm(1000, 0, 1)
hist(D, freq = FALSE)

Central Limit Theorem

  • The sum of a large number of random variables (even if their own individual distributions are not themselves normal) will have an approximately normal distribution
  • A measurement that represents the sum of a number of different factors could be expected to have an approximately normal distribution
  • As the sample size increases, the sampling distribution of the mean from a random sample of size n more closely approximates a normal distribution
    • Even if the population distribution is non-normal, as sample size increases the sampling distribution of the mean becomes closer to normal
    • This is why, even if there is a departure from normality, some parametric tests still are robust, because with increasing sample size comes an increasing approximation of normality
  • If sample data is approximately normal, than so will the sampling distribution
  • This allows for the use of statistical treatments that assume a normal distribution even when samples are drawn from a population that is not normally distributed
size=20 
repeats=10000
v=runif(size*repeats)
hist(v)


w=matrix(v,size, repeats)
y=colSums(w)
hist(y,freq=FALSE,ann=FALSE)

Parametric versus Nonparametric Tests

  • Parametric tests assume a specific underlying distribution, whereas parametric tests do not
  • Parametric assumptions:
    • Normal distribution
    • Homoscedasticity
    • Interval scale
    • Independence
  • Parametric tests are suitable for continuous data and if data are normally distributed
    • Even if your data are skewed and your sample sizes are sufficient but you do not exactly have a normal distribution, then many parametric tests are still robust enough to handle these violations of assumptions
    • Parametric tests are often more suitable if variances are different between groups
    • Parametric tests typically have greater statistical power
  • Nonparametric tests are suitable for categorical data and if data are nonnormally distributed or outliers are present
    • Even if continuous data, if your sample sizes are small, nonparametric tests may be better suited

  • Kolmogorov-Smirnov test: examines the maximum difference between the observed distribution and expected cumulative-normal distribution; considered a distance test
    • The Lilliefors' adjustment used to calculate the expected distribution from sample parameters
    • Less powerful than many other alternatives, but popular
    • Can be tested for non-normal distributions as well

ks.test(x = BACups$RD,y = pnorm)

alternative hypothesis: two-sided

alternative hypothesis: two-sided
  • Shapiro-Wilk's: compares the scores of your distribution to a normal distribution with the same mean and standard deviation; assesses skewness and kurtosis
    • Limitations: with large sample sizes, significant results can occur due to slight deviations from normality, not great with discrete data
#shapiro.test(variable)
shapiro.test(BACups$RD)


    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  BACups$RD
W = 0.89773, p-value = 0.0001088

#if you want to do this by group, not just a total

#by(variable, group, shapiro.test)

  • D'Agostino Omnibus (\( K^2 \)): combines the D'Agostino Skewness and Kurtosis tests; considered to be a powerful test

    • Particularly helpful if you have many identical values in the data set
      • Skewness test: null hypothesis is that the distribution is approximately normal; tests if the distribution is symmetrical

\( z_{s} \) = \( d ln \left (\frac{T}{a} + \sqrt(\frac{T}{a}^2 +1)\right) \)

  • Kurtosis test: tests if the distribution is approximately mesokurtic; in a normal dstribution the kurtosis value is 3 so such a test examines if the distribution is significantly different than 3

\( z_{k} \) = $\displaystyle \frac {(1 - \frac{2}{9A})({1-{2}{A}{1+G\sqrt(\frac{2}{A-4})}{{1}{3}}}{\sqrt({2}{9A})})

\( K^2 \) = \( z_{s}^{2} \) + z_{k}{2}

Testing for the Assumption of Homogeneity of Variance

  • Homoscedasticity/Homogeneity of variance: refers to the fact that as the value of a variable changes, the variance remains the same

  • Levene's test: tests the null hypothesis that the variances in different groups are equal - Conducts a one-way ANOVA on the deviation scores (the absolute difference between each score and the mean of their group) - Not robust to nonnormality unless sample sizes are equal

\( Z_{ij} = |Y_{ij} - \overline{Y}_{ij}| \)

Are my data normal?

library(car)
#leveneTest(outcome variable, group, center = median/mean)

If it wasn't normal, or we'd rather use median (if other variables are non-normal and we want to use the same technique for all variables):

  • Brown-Forsythe procedure: adaptation to Levene's test - Robust to nonnormality - Also essentially an ANOVA, but with the median

\( Z_{ij} = |Y_{ij} - Mdn_{j}| \)

  • Bartlett's test: less sensitive to departures from normality, but has more statistical power when data come from a normal distribution; does not require equal sample sizes

T = $\displaystyle \frac {(N-k) ln s_{p}2 - \( \sum_{i=1}^{k} (N_{i}-1)ln s_{i}^{2}} \){1+ \( \frac {1}{3(k-1)}}((\sum_{i=1}^{k} \frac{1}{N_{i}-1}- \frac {1}{N-k})) \)

library(car)
#bartlett.test(variable, group, dataset)
bartlett.test(x = BACups$RD, g = BACups$Phase, BACups)

  • Plotting residuals
#Create linear models to then plot residuals
#aov(variable ~ groupcolumn, data)

result <- aov(formula = BACups$RD ~ BACups$Phase)
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
plot(result)

Residuals vs. Fitted

  • Shows the variability in residuals. No variability would be an observation along the 0 line. Above the line indicates the observation was greater than the mean, below the line indicates the observation was smaller than the mean.

Normal Q-Q

  • Compares the residuals to a normal distribution to see if there is any deviation from what would be expected for the residuals

Scale-Location

  • Also indicates the degree of heteroscedasticity. A line straight across has homoscedasticity, whereas a curved line indicates variation.

Residuals vs. Leverage

  • Indicates if certain observations are having a greater influence on the estimation of regression coefficients

If you want to compare homoscedasticity against two variables:

Size-correcting Data

For example, males and females

  • Analyze males and females separately
  • Sexually dimorphic variables could be removed from the analysis

  • Sex-specific z-scores

    • These are calculated based on each group's arithmetic means
    • Can only be performed on those with a sex estimate (males and females, and probable males and probable females if you are comfortable combining those with estimates)

  • When data are all approximately normal, but you want to create the same scale without changing the shape, use z-scores

    • Takes values and converts their normal distribution to that of a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1
    • Unitless

\( z_{i} \)= \( \frac {X_{i} - \mu_{X}}{\sigma_{X}} \)

Outliers

  • A data point or observation that is extremely different than the rest of the collected data

  • Why is it important to identify them?

    • They may skew the data, including descriptive statistics, as well as multivariate techniques
    • They may represent data input errors (either completely wrong data put in or maybe data was put in the incorrect cells)

  • How to identify outliers

    • One idea is to use 1.5 x IQR and subtract this from the first quartile (anything less than this are low mild outliers) and to take 1.5 x IQR and add this to the third quartile (anything over this are high mild outliers)
    • If you multiple the IQR by 3, these are considered extreme outliers

  • So what to do with outliers?
    • Depends on person to person
    • Remove if you can identify they are related to transcription errors
    • Trimming of data set
    • Are they statistically outliers but practically it is feasible?

Shape Transformations for Data

  • Assist with transforming data that are non-normally distributed
    • This can be done to allow for parametric tests if you would rather not use nonparametric tests or if you want to use certain statistical tests that are robust against outliers
    • Linear regression requires linear relationships between variables; therefore, transforming data can allow for two non-linearly related variables to now be put in with a regression (Warning: this can make otherwise additive errors into multiplicative errors when using logarithmic transformations; better to use nonlinear regression)
    • Can allow for weights to be equal across variables

Ways to Transform Data

  • When right-skewed
    • Taking the roots (squared or cubed or higher) of data for moderate asymmetry or unequal variances; can handle 0 but cannot handle negative numbers
